iter John Burroughs, British activist Edward Carpenter, and the notorious Oscar Wilde. Despite their particular needs, they all viewed Whitman as the author of a new poetic scripture and prophet of a modern liberal spirituality.Worshipping Walt presents a colorful portrait of an era of intense religious, political, and sexual passions, shedding new light on why Whitman's work continues to appeal to so many.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aInfluence (Literary, artistic, etc.) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh  aA Clergyman's Daughter.  aAbolitionism.  aAeschylus.  aAestheticism.  aAfterword.  aAllen Say.  aAndrew Greeley.  aArts and Crafts movement.  aBrief Encounter.  aCharles Dickens.  aChivalric romance.  aCollege Garden.  aComplete Poems.  aComrade.  aContemporary society.  aDamnation.  aDaniel Berrigan.  aDemocratic Vistas.  aDrum-Taps.  aEdward Bellamy.  aEdward Carpenter.  aElias Hicks.  aEnglish poetry.  aEugene V. Debs.  aFanny Fern.  aFrançois Rabelais.  aG. (novel).  aGary Snyder.  aGeorge Whitman.  aGifford Lectures.  aGilded Age.  aGoldman.  aH. L. Mencken.  aHack writer.  aHenry David Thoreau.  aHerbert Read.  aHis Family.  aHis Favorite.  aHorace Traubel.  aHorace Walpole.  aHoward University.  aI Wish (manhwa).  aIbid (short story).  aJeremiad.  aJohn Addington Symonds.  aJohn Ruskin.  aJustin Kaplan.  aKarl Shapiro.  aLamarckism.  aLarry Kramer.  aLeaves of Grass.  aLife and Letters.  aLondoners.  aLooking Backward.  aLord Alfred Douglas.  aMadness and Civilization.  aMary Lamb.  aMemoir.  aMoral treatment.  aMr.  aMuscular Christianity.  aNew Poems.  aNew Thought.  aNoble savage.  aOscar Wilde.  aParody.  aPercy Bysshe Shelley.  aPhrenology.  aPoet